    <h4 class="news-story-title">
        
            <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://hir.harvard.edu/is-beijing-creating-a-new-sino-russian-world-order/">Is Beijing Creating a New Sino-Russian World Order?: The Russian Invasion of Ukraine Might Change Beijing’s Calculus for Taiwan and the United States</a>
        
    </h4>

<div class="row">
    
        <div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">
            <div class="news-story-byline">
                
                    
                        <a rel="nofollow" class="timeago" title="Mar 08, 2022" href="/link/oOdqS6/is-beijing-creating-a-new-sino-russian-world-order-the-russian-invasion-of-ukraine-might-change-beijings-calculus-for-taiwan-and-the-united-states">2 days ago</a>
                    
                    
                
                
                    
                    
                
                
                    
                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                    
                
                



    
    
        <a href="/media-outlet/hir-harvard" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Harvard International Review</a>
        
    
    


            </div>
            
            
                
                    When the invading Russian forces brutally advanced into Ukraine, the Chinese Foreign Ministry announced: “Taiwan is not Ukraine.” For Beijing, Taiwan has always been “an inalienable part of China.” This claim seems to portray Taiwan as a very different case than Ukraine. From the Chinese perspective, Beijing’s assault to unify the breakaway province would be an internal matter—not an international conflict.
                
                
            
        </div>
    
    
