    <h4 class="news-story-title">
        
            <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://hir.harvard.edu/artful-resistance-how-afghan-women-are-wielding-art-against-the-taliban/">Artful Resistance: How Afghan Women are Wielding Art Against the Taliban</a>
        
    </h4>

<div class="row">
    
        <div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">
            <div class="news-story-byline">
                
                    
                        <a rel="nofollow" class="timeago" title="Mar 02, 2022" href="/link/oOx5Mt/artful-resistance-how-afghan-women-are-wielding-art-against-the-taliban">8 days ago</a>
                    
                    
                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                    
                
                
                    
                        


<div class="mr-byline ">
    By <a href="/addie-esposito" target="_blank">Addie Esposito</a>
</div>


                    
                    
                
                
                    
                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                    
                
                



    
    
        <a href="/media-outlet/hir-harvard" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Harvard International Review</a>
        
    
    


            </div>
            
            
                
                    “We’re not victims—we’re champions. We’ve fought hard for everything we’ve accomplished. But people expect us to be satisfied with basic rights, nothing more.”Rada Akbar, an Afghan artist known for her visual art and photography, encourages the world to see the strength in Afghan women. Akbar’s work includes portraits of Afghan women, documentation of female resistance to the Taliban, activist messages, and powerful exposure of the dangers plaguing Afghan women.
                
                
            
